<tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>638</anchor> <rss>jms-00IK.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Notation</taxon> <addr>jms-00IK</addr>  <route>jms-00IK.xml</route> <date><year>2024</year> <month>1</month> <day>17</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> <contributor><link href="marcelofiore.xml" type="local" marcelofiore="addr">Marcelo Fiore</link></contributor></authors> <title>Internal diagrams of <link href="jms-00I7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00I7" title="Relation">relations</link></title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>A useful way to visualise a <link href="jms-00I7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00I7" title="Relation">relation</link> between two sets is by means of <em><strong>internal diagrams</strong></em>: each set is depicted as a blob containing its elements, and lines are drawn from the elements of one blob to the elements of the second blob when they are related.</p><p>In particular, let <tex>R \colon \mathbb {N} \mathbin { \nrightarrow } \mathbb {Z}</tex> be the following <link href="jms-00I7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00I7" title="Relation">relation</link>:</p><tex display="block">
 R =  { \mathopen {} \left \{ 
   { \mathopen {} \left ( 0,0 \right ) \mathclose {}} ,
   { \mathopen {} \left ( 1,-1 \right ) \mathclose {}} ,
   { \mathopen {} \left ( 0,1 \right ) \mathclose {}} ,
   { \mathopen {} \left ( 1,2 \right ) \mathclose {}} ,
   { \mathopen {} \left ( 1,1 \right ) \mathclose {}} ,
   { \mathopen {} \left ( 2,1 \right ) \mathclose {}} 
  \right \} \mathclose {}} 
</tex><p>We can depict <tex>R</tex> by the following internal diagram:</p>
  
